menu "breadboard: bb_data_http"

config BB_DATA_HTTP_MAX_CLIENTS
    int "Max concurrent SSE/WS clients"
    default 2
    range 1 16
    help
        Maximum number of simultaneous bb_data_http subscribers (SSE or WS).
        Sizes the compile-time client-slot pool; bb_data_http_init()'s cfg
        may only shrink this at runtime, never grow it.

config BB_DATA_HTTP_OUTBOUND_CAPACITY
    int "Per-client outbound queue entry capacity"
    default 8
    range 1 64
    help
        Max number of rendered frames a client's outbound bb_queue holds at
        once (B1-1031 byte/age backpressure extension). On overflow the
        oldest queued frame is evicted (BB_QUEUE_EVICT_OLDEST).

config BB_DATA_HTTP_OUTBOUND_ENTRY_MAX
    int "Per-client outbound max rendered frame size (bytes)"
    default 512
    range 64 4096
    help
        Maximum size of a single rendered frame (one key's value) buffered
        for a client. A render_fn output larger than this is rejected by
        bb_queue_push (truncated counter incremented, frame dropped).

config BB_DATA_HTTP_OUTBOUND_MAX_BYTES
    int "Per-client outbound total byte budget"
    default 4096
    range 512 32768
    help
        Total payload-byte budget across a client's queued outbound frames
        (B1-1031). Eviction (oldest first) fires on this budget OR the entry
        capacity above, whichever is hit first.

config BB_DATA_HTTP_EVENT_RING_CAPACITY
    int "Shared EVENT ring entry capacity"
    default 16
    range 1 64
    help
        Max number of rendered EVENT frames held at once in the single
        shared ring fed by every EVENT-kind attached key (B1-1032). On
        overflow the oldest entry is evicted; any client whose own cursor
        had not yet drained an evicted entry counts it as dropped (see
        bb_data_http_client_dropped_count()). bb_data_http_cfg_t may only
        shrink this at runtime, never grow it.

# ESP-IDF backend (B1-1033 first bench-flash de-risk, design KB 1447):
# platform/espidf/bb_data_http/bb_data_http_espidf.c only -- no effect on
# the pure core or any other platform.

config BB_DATA_HTTP_SEND_TIMEOUT_MS
    int "SSE client send timeout (ms)"
    default 20
    range 1 1000
    help
        SO_SNDTIMEO set on a client's socket at connect. Deliberately short:
        the ONE shared broadcaster task pays this timeout per stalled client
        per sweep, so BB_DATA_HTTP_MAX_CLIENTS * this value must stay well
        under BB_DATA_HTTP_SWEEP_INTERVAL_MS (default 2*20ms=40ms < 50ms).

config BB_DATA_HTTP_RECV_TIMEOUT_MS
    int "SSE client receive timeout (ms)"
    default 30000
    range 1000 120000
    help
        SO_RCVTIMEO set on a client's socket at connect -- surfaces a dead
        or half-open peer via the socket layer itself, independent of the
        broadcaster's own peer-liveness pre-pass.

config BB_DATA_HTTP_SWEEP_INTERVAL_MS
    int "Broadcaster sweep interval (ms)"
    default 50
    range 10 1000
    help
        vTaskDelay() cadence of the single broadcaster task between
        peer-liveness pre-pass + bb_data_http_sweep_step() calls.

config BB_DATA_HTTP_TASK_STACK_BYTES
    int "Broadcaster task stack (bytes)"
    default 4096
    range 2048 16384
    help
        Stack budget for the single, process-lifetime broadcaster task
        (bb_task_create, BB_TASK_BACKING_DYNAMIC).

config BB_DATA_HTTP_TASK_PRIORITY
    int "Broadcaster task priority"
    default 4
    range 1 10
    help
        FreeRTOS priority of the broadcaster task -- below lwip's own
        internal task priority by default.

config BB_DATA_HTTP_RENDER_SCRATCH_BYTES
    int "Render scratch buffer size (bytes)"
    default 256
    range 32 2048
    help
        Fixed-size CALLER-OWNED scratch bb_data_render() gathers into before
        rendering (KB 1447 fork #1: a fixed Kconfig stopgap, not a per-key
        snap_size getter -- deferred to the B1-1045 cutover). A binding
        whose desc->snap_size exceeds this returns BB_ERR_NO_SPACE from
        bb_data_render(); bb_data_http_sweep_step() leaves that key's dirty
        bit set on any render_fn failure, so it is retried (and logged,
        rate-limited) every subsequent sweep rather than silently dropped.
        Default 256 covers the largest wire type attached today (the "log"
        key's bb_log_event_wire_t at 220 bytes, B1-1045 PR-4) with margin;
        bb_data_http_attach_sized() FAILS LOUD at attach time (ESP_LOGE +
        BB_ERR_NO_SPACE, not a silent forever-failing render) if a future
        binding's snap_size exceeds this.

endmenu
